### Vectors in Rust

`Vec<T>` is a growable, heap-allocated array type. It stores elements of the same type in contiguous memory.

---

### Vector Operations

| Method | Description |
|--------|-------------|
| `Vec::new()` | Create empty vector |
| `vec![]` | Macro to create with initial values |
| `push(val)` | Add element to end |
| `pop()` | Remove and return last element |
| `get(index)` | Return `Option<&T>` at index |
| `len()` | Number of elements |
| `is_empty()` | Check if empty |
| `contains(&val)` | Check if contains value |
| `remove(index)` | Remove at index (shifts elements) |
| `sort()` | Sort in place |

---

### Examples

```rust
let mut v1: Vec<i32> = Vec::new();
v1.push(1);
v1.push(2);

let v2 = vec![1, 2, 3, 4, 5];

// Accessing elements
let third = &v2[2];             // panics if out of bounds
let third = v2.get(2);          // returns Option<&i32>

// Iterating
for i in &v2 {
    println!("{}", i);
}

// Iterating with mutation
for i in &mut v { 
    *i *= 2; 
}

// Collecting from iterator
let squares: Vec<i32> = (0..10).map(|x| x * x).collect();
```

> **Key Point:** Use `vec![]` macro for creating vectors with initial values. Prefer `get()` over indexing for safe access. Vectors own their data and drop all elements when they go out of scope.

codeExample:
fn main() {
    let mut numbers = vec![5, 2, 8, 1, 9];

    numbers.sort();
    println!("Sorted: {:?}", numbers);

    numbers.push(3);
    println!("After push: {:?}", numbers);

    if let Some(last) = numbers.pop() {
        println!("Popped: {}", last);
    }

    println!("Length: {}", numbers.len());
}
